column109: I am getting better at expressing my opinions and thoughts to other people. column109: My analytical and introspective nature allow me to constantly reevaluate and improve myself. My humility allows me to empathize with and gives me compassion for other people. My perfectionism wastes time and energy and also causes me to procrastinate because I can sometimes make simple tasks more complicated and unenjoyable than necessary.

Since the last survey, I've continually examined my personality and my interactions with other people. I continue to try and become a better person than before. During this search, I felt that my tolerance of others is one of my best qualities because it keeps conflicts from happening between me and others. From this tolerance, I can determine how to best aide others instead of trying to one-up them. Additionally with others, I'm enthusiastic to become friends with them. Instead of looking for conflict, I go for a community environment of working together. However I still have my flaws which I definitely need to work on. I chose easily distracted because it seems I'm always not doing what I should be doing because I'm distracted with something else. For example, just writing these paragraphs took so much longer because I looked at Facebook way too many times. My other flaw is talking without thinking because, while I'm enthusiastic to be with others, many times I let my mouth run before realizing the consequences. My girlfriend also comments on this flaw frequently. My goal is to learn to concentrate and think before I speak - or at least assess the consequences more. While I answered previous questionnaires with somewhat different qualities/traits, I don't think my personality has changed since the last time, I've only grown in understanding of my personality.

column109: A lot of people around me tend to refer to me as the smartest person they know: I have a lot of knowledge from many different areas, which frequently comes into play.  My intelligence has also impacted my abilities in social circles, since I tend to be able to fit in with different circles simply by knowing information about their shared interests.  Along with this, my open-mindedness has proven invaluable.  Not only has it earned me friends and a career, but it has also opened my eyes to many different types of people that many others close themselves off to.  However, I am told that I can be quite condescending, which is the hubris of intelligence.  Sometimes I act like I am smarter than others, since I explain things they already understand.  In my mind, it just reads as making sure we are on the same page, but apparently it comes of as condescending.  Along with this, I tend to think about the facts before I speak.  Although I am very good at understanding human emotion when it is presented to me, I am not the best at predicting it.  Thus I often do not realize that people will be so negatively impacted by just a statement of the facts.

column109: Amiable and dedicated are my strongest and best qualities because they embody who I am as a person. They make up my daily interactions with other people and dictate my course of action in any given situation. I never find myself lacking in coming through for a friend or on any level of commitment that I make.  Stubborn and Perfectionism are my worst traits because they can massively set me back on the way to my goals. If I get set in something that I'm not overly fond of, or develop a dislike for, I can be an incorrigable pain to myself in trying to break that mold. If I find myself consistently getting hung up over minor inconsequential details purely because of the imperfection I find in them, which realistically I should not be bothered by but do anyway.

These are the two traits that I'm most proud of, because they take so much strength and courage to really truly carry them out. I spent the last year taking care of my ex, who, while we were dating, had suicidal depression. I took him to the hospital multiple times and (this is the least braggy way I can put this) he probably wouldn't be alive if I hadn't been there. These are the traits that make me myself, and make me feel like I am giving as much to the world as possible. I do have an anxiety disorder that can make me extremely nervous at times, and it impacts my behavior and cognitive functioning more than I would like it to. It bothers me, and I am constantly trying to find ways to decrease my levels of anxiety. I can also be disorganized at times, to the point that I miss appointments or have to very quickly finish assignments and such. I've started making lists and being as organized as possible recently, and it is helping.
column113: took my ex to the hospital 3 times, once for a suicide attempt, twice for suicidal ideation

column109: I think that one of my best qualities is that I'm caring because when I talk to people, I really want to hear what they say and what they're going through. I listen to them fully and completely because I would like to help others see the positive side of things if I can. I also really value my friends and my family and I make sure that these people know that I care about them and their wellbeing. I said that passionate was one of my best qualities because I think that one of the things that makes me interesting is that when my interest is piqued by something, I look into it in depth and detail. I really love talking about certain topics, whether I saw a news clip on the radio and investigated online to find out more about it, or I read an article for a class that I'm currently obsessed with and I want to discuss it with someone. I think that my passion for certain things shines through when I'm talking about them, and I can go off on crazy tangents from these things, but my friends love me so that's all I need.  I said that one of my worst qualities is that I am distractible. I think that I try to pay attention to what I'm doing as much as possible, but sometimes I get distracted. I feel really bad because sometimes I'm talking to someone and my eye will catch a bright color going by and they think I'm not paying attention to them, but I really am. I said that being nervous is one of the my worst qualities because I tend to get nervous in social situations and I don't like that I get uncomfortable and anxious when a lot of other people seem like they're doing fine. I also wish that I didn't get so nervous about public speaking and talking in large groups of people.

column109: I have been through a lot of suffering and that has made me compassionate. I am able to see things from someone else's perspective and feel things the way they do. I feel others' feelings. It makes me kind, patient, and warm, because I can feel what others have been through. I understand the human condition. When I say I am strong, I do not mean physically. I'm actually physically quite weak. But my character is strong. I have persevered through family hardships and severe mental illness. I have survived through times when I honestly did my best not to. And I've spent the past year working to turn my life around.  Sometimes I worry that I think too highly of myself and that I take my privlige for granted. I'm also quite judgmental of people before I get to know them. It's internal judgment, meaning that I think judgmental thoughts but I try very hard not to let them affect my actions. I have judgments in my mind, as all humans do, but I do not act on them.

column109: I think that being open and being a leader are two things that go hand in hand that I do well in. In order to lead, one must be willing to open yourself up to others, to allow them to relate and trust you. I also feel that opening up about my weaknesses help other people with their own. This is something I am good at.  As for being scheduled and non-adaptive, they are almost the same thing. I have difficulty adapting to things that don't fit into my schedule and find myself fitting people into "time-slots" instead of just maintaining relationships as they come. My life seems to be timed.

I like laughing and making other people laugh. I often make people laugh and I am not afraid of looking silly. I also always try to help other people. I am always available for my friends and listen to them.  I am of an anxious nature, I worry a lot about what could go wrong in a situation. column109: I said that my forgiving nature is one of my best qualities because I recently was wronged by some people, and many told me that if they had been in my shoes, they would not have forgiven the people, but it was really important to me to go ahead and forgive them. It wasn't an easy decision, but I am happy that I was able to do so. I said that compassion is one of my best qualities because I think it's really important to see things from other people's persepctive and to do your best to lend a hand whenever and whereever you can, and I like that I genuinely care about the well-being of others.  I said that my inattentiveness is one of my worst traits because I have noticed that I have a tendency to not really listen when people are talking to me. I not and smile, and comment appropriately, but when they walk away, or the next day, or a week later, I realise that I have no idea what I talked about with that person. I don't remember the details of people's live that they tell me about, and tehn I feel really bad when they remember something I told them about myself, and remember to take the time to follow up on something I may have said I was struggling with, but I can't remember specific details about their lives. And I don't mean to come off as shallow or uncaring, because I really do care about what they have to say, what people are going through, and what they tell me. I really do care about people's personal lives, I just can't seem to remember, just like I can't seem to remember names to save my life. So that is something that I have started trying to make a conscious effort to work on. I said that my other worst quality is my idecisiveness. Decision take me a very long time, even for very simple things like which brand of cheese I want to buy. And it get very annoying to myself, so I'm sure it must be irritating for other people when I am holding things up because I can't make a decsion.

column109: I am hardworking, but also have a good sense of humor that allows me not to become too stressed out by my workload.  I sometimes refuse to acknowledge other valid viewpoints because I can be stubborn and insensitive.

By original I mean that I am able to see things where there is nothing. I am not afraid to make ideas into reality, I like to explore and to experiment. If something hasn't been tried, might as well try it and see if it works. To some degree, this relates to a personal interest in putting more things in the world that fascinate others. Everyone has so much they could be fascinated in if they opened their eyes, I think. I am easily fascinated by most things. I knit the sweaters on the bunny statue and I ran around campus as a ghost with my buddy pacman on Halloween because I want the world to be filled with original and fascinating things, and if they aren't there, I will put them there.   Thoughtful was a tricky word, I meant to say that I put a lot of thought into all things. Actually I maybe should have said understanding. I am very aware of the people I am around, and that I don't know everything.  I am the least road rage effected person ever, I am never in a position to make judgements about other drivers because I literally know nothing about whats going on with them, who knows if they picked up an injured bird, have a crazy child fight going on in the backseat, are rushing to aid an injured relative. I err on the side of caution, and unless anyone is literally putting my life in danger, I'm quite tolerant. I am not empathetic, which will come up momentarily, but I'm not at all judgmental. I like to think about what is going on with everyone and just hold it in my mind as I observe the world.  Is there a word for not being empathetic? Thats what I meant. I just can't feel other people's emotions. Its that simple. It doesn't really bother me much, but it makes me sad when it makes my significant other sad that I can't empathize with things in his life. Sometimes I feel like I have an easier time imagining emotions of inanimate objects or animals than people, because people-emotions seem quite illogical at times because people have so much power to change their situation. I can't remember what I was supposed to be empathizing with him about, but for instance I have a friend right now in an emotional crisis regarding a relationship and I can talk with her about it, but I really just can't feel with her. I still don't really see this as a bad thing. Its just a thing. And I don't think I expect people to empathize with me either, people can only really really understand themselves.   Reclusive, I like being alone but this is related to social anxiety. I avoid spaces, activities, etc. because of social anxiety. Being around people I don't exactly know but should maybe know is uncomfortable, I'd rather be with total strangers or close friends, small talk is my least favorite thing. I sometimes find isolated places to eat alone because if I was eating alone in a public, visible space, people might see me and try to join me. I also do actually like social interaction most of the time, so this doesn't totally make sense and thats why I put it as a negative thing. There is nothing wrong with being alone and enjoying being alone, but being afraid of people in this way is rather maladaptive and nonsensical.

column321: This has been an interesting adventure in personality surveys. I'm excited to read about some of the conclusions from this study someday in the yonder future.

column109: When it comes to my career and personal achievement, I am very determined and intelligent. I tend to be very reliable and consistent in my work. I am thorough and detail -oriented. I am also a lover of knowledge, so over time, I gain a lot of knowledge; hence, I am intelligent through my dedication to my studies and willingness to discover new things.   However, I am usually neurotic. I am often easily nervious or anxious, but I am not sure why. I did not used to be this way. I have also become closed to certain individuals because I judge them. I am currently working on these traits since I know that I have them. These traits often hinder my group interactions and social relationships, both with people I know and acquaintances.

Thomas thinks I'm witty. I think I'm analytical and have a very organized way of thinking. I'm lazy and unmotivated when it comes to school and I'm moody so I get angry at Thomas a lot or upset and sad.

People have always thought of me as inventive and humorous.   I have heard a lot about my unique sense of humor and the ways it affects my creative process.   People tell me I have a dry,  sarcastic wit that while abrasive and crude,  can be hilarious.  I often forget to focus on the ways my behavior affects others, and forget to treat others with understanding when I'm angry.   Sometimes i feel argumentative and don't consider the feelings of others,  and that has jeopardized my relationships in the past

I am compassionate with anyone and everyone I deal with, or at least try to be. I am able to realte to the difficulties many people have had because of personal experiences, so I try my hardest to not get carried away with emotions when helping people talk through their problems. I believe that when my friends or even strangers need to talk things through, I am able to put aside my own struggles to genuinely care for them and be there for them. Many of my friends have told me that I am a likeable and genuine person.   I am blunt with my friends especially, and also with people that I don't know as well a lot. This goes hand in hand with the importance I place on being authentic. When asked for my opinion, I try to present it in a way that is not hurtful, but I do tell the truth. I take honesty very seriously, and I think sometimes people may hear something they don't like to hear from me. But for the most part, people who come to me for advice appreciate that I tell the truth like it is. One trait I am definitely trying to work on is my untimeliness. It's not a good quality to have that I show up a minute or two late to class or meetings. I don't know why it is so hard for me to leave that minute or two earlier, but it is the biggest thing that I'm working on right now.

column109: I think that being compassionate makes me very relatable and helps me to be a good friend to those around me. People feel very comfortable opening up and sharing with me because of my compassionate nature it also helps me to reach out to those who are not necessarily me friends. It helps me to help those around me and give back to the communities i'm in. Being fun is also a really good quality to have because people will enjoy themselves when there around you. column109: I feel like the best thing I can offer to my friends (and even people I don't know as well) is support and validation for their own endeavors. I tend to put myself last, which is something I like about myself, but when my needs fall so far below my other priorities, it affects me and my ability to help others in a more profound way than I'd like. column109: Intelligence and creativity are connected, but different aspects of more or less the same thing. My intelligence is what has gotten me to where I am in life, and is what I consider to provide for my future. I can analyze a situation and stake a claim on it based on the information I have and the logic I can use to support my reasoning. It is practical for myself and for helping others, and is the most useful aspect of my personality. Creativity is less practical, but still important for me to be able to enjoy life, as well as what might potentially make me interesting to others. I am able to create new things, experiment, explore, and--combined with my intelligence--articulate ideas. Both intelligence and creativity are what determine who I am and what I can accomplish.  By over-certainty, I mean an insistence that I am right--not quite vanity or arrogance, but at least a stubbornness when dealing with others. Because I rely so heavily on my intelligence and my own reasoning, I often ignore or discount what others have to say because I have already found the "right" solution. By anger, I partially mean how quick I can be to anger, but also how my emotions can get in the way of my interpersonal relationships. Multiple friends have stated that they fear me and my reactions to criticism--my anger, and how easily it can be awakened, scares them. Perhaps a better trait to have selected would have been "moodiness," because it is not just anger, but melancholy and sadness as well that can disrupt my interactions with others. But anger seems to be the most problematic for others.
